Issues.Body:
### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

@angular/forms/signals

### Description

As of 20.0.3, in my Signal Form example, if my field is **disabled** with schema (_SchemaPathTree_) and I try to get the form's value with `form().value()`, it will include disabled fields as well which is not compatible with Reactive Forms.

```
readonly model = signal<{ name: string; address: string }>({ name: '', address: '' });

readonly form = form(this.model, schema => {
    required(schema.name);
    disabled(schema.address);
});

console.log(form().value()); // { name: '', address: '' }

```

Usecase:
Migrating Reactive Forms to Signal Forms.

### Proposed solution

We could get the raw value from the model's _getter_.
`form().value()` could return only non-disabled value.

### Alternatives considered

Implement `rawValue() `getter as well to make it compatible with Reactive Forms.

### Describe the problem that you experienced

I'm using signal forms in a large and complicated model. They are way nicer to use than their predecessors! I cannot however figure out how to define validation rules for array subobjects. I've searched all the documentation that currently exists, and tried a lot of AI hallucination ideas... still not able to determine the correct way to do it.

<img width="733" height="240" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/ad7f9257-017b-44de-b5a3-677ac800ce0b" />

All the top-level properties get validation properties applied (like min/max), but the array items do not.

StackBlitz: <https://stackblitz.com/edit/stackblitz-starters-8h2mho4b?file=src%2Fmain.ts>

<details><summary>Minimal Reproduction Code</summary>
<p>

```ts
import { Component, signal } from '@angular/core';
import { bootstrapApplication } from '@angular/platform-browser';
import { Field, form, required, min, max } from '@angular/forms/signals';

export interface Model {
  propertyA: string;
  propertyB: number;
  propertyC: boolean;
  propertyD: Array<{
    subPropA: string;
    subPropB: number;
    subPropC: boolean;
  }>;
}

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  imports: [Field],
  template: `
    <h1>Example Signal Form</h1>

    <form (submit)="onSubmit(model()); $event.preventDefault();">
      <label>
        Property A:
        <input [field]="modelForm.propertyA" />
      </label>
      <label>
        Property B:
        <input type="number" [field]="modelForm.propertyB" />
      </label>
      <label>
        Property C:
        <input type="checkbox" [field]="modelForm.propertyC" />
      </label>
      <section>
        <h2>Property D:</h2>
        @for(valueForm of modelForm.propertyD; track $index) {
          <div>
            <label>
              Sub-Property A:
              <input [field]="valueForm.subPropA" />
            </label>
            <label>
              Sub-Property B:
              <input type="number" [field]="valueForm.subPropB" />
            </label>
            <label>
              Sub-Property C:
              <input type="checkbox" [field]="valueForm.subPropC" />
            </label>
          </div>
        }
      </section>
      <button>Submit</button>
    </form>
  `,
})
export class App {
  readonly model = signal<Model>({
    propertyA: 'abc',
    propertyB: 123,
    propertyC: true,
    propertyD: [
      {
        subPropA: 'def',
        subPropB: 456,
        subPropC: false,
      },
      {
        subPropA: 'ghi',
        subPropB: 789,
        subPropC: true,
      },
    ],
  });
  readonly modelForm = form(this.model, (path) => {
    required(path.propertyA);
    min(path.propertyB, 0);
    max(path.propertyB, 1000);

    //// CAN'T FIGURE OUT HOW TO DO SOMETHING LIKE THIS:
    // path.propertyD.children.forEach(c => {
    //   required(c.subPropA);
    //   min(c.subPropB, 0);
    //   max(c.subPropB, 1);
    // });
  });

  onSubmit(value: Model) {
    console.log('Submitted!', { value });
  }
}

bootstrapApplication(App);
```

</p>
</details> 

### Enter the URL of the topic with the problem

https://angular.dev/essentials/signal-forms

##  Update:

I did figure out how to get this to work! But I still couldn't find a single example of this in the documentation. Here's what I did:

```ts
  readonly modelForm = form(this.model, (path) => {
    required(path.propertyA);
    min(path.propertyB, 0);
    max(path.propertyB, 1000);

    applyEach(path.propertyD, (item) => {
      required(item.subPropA);
      min(item.subPropB, 0);
      max(item.subPropB, 1000);
    });
  });
```

### Command

lint

### Description

Now `ng lint` command generates 
- JavaScript configuration
- with `require` syntax (which is kind of legacy or Node.js thing)
- with deprecated [`tseslint.config`](https://typescript-eslint.io/packages/typescript-eslint/#config-deprecated)
---
So instead of this
```javascript
// eslint.config.js
// @ts-check
const eslint = require("@eslint/js");
const tseslint = require("typescript-eslint");
const angular = require("angular-eslint");

module.exports = tseslint.config(
  {
    files: ["**/*.ts"],
    extends: [
      eslint.configs.recommended,
      ...tseslint.configs.recommended,
      ...tseslint.configs.stylistic,
      ...angular.configs.tsRecommended,
    ],
    processor: angular.processInlineTemplates,
    rules: {
      "@angular-eslint/directive-selector": [
        "error",
        {
          type: "attribute",
          prefix: "app",
          style: "camelCase",
        },
      ],
      "@angular-eslint/component-selector": [
        "error",
        {
          type: "element",
          prefix: "app",
          style: "kebab-case",
        },
      ],
    },
  },
  {
    files: ["**/*.html"],
    extends: [
      ...angular.configs.templateRecommended,
      ...angular.configs.templateAccessibility,
    ],
    rules: {},
  }
);
```

